The following is a copy of leaflets that were dropped alongside jungle trails in South vietnam near the Dai Loc, Da Nang  area during late Novemeber 1966-December 1968. THEY ARE HERE REPRODUCED AS THEY WERE WRITTEN.<br><br>
                     Policy towards US and Satellite POWs<br>
                                    In South Vietnam<br><br>
Based on the humanitarian and lenient policy of the SVN-NFL, the High Command of the SVN-LA has stipulated the following points.<br><br>
1. The US and other satellite officers and men who lay-down their arms at the battlefield will not be killed and will be transferred to safe places.<br><br>
(on the other side of the leaflet it continues)<br><br>
2. POWs will be well-treated - will not be tortured or insulted and will be given medical care in case of sickness.<br>
3. All their personal belongings such as; money, gold watches, pens and other private souvenir will not be deprived<br>
4. POWs are allowed to communicate news and write to their families and friends.<br>
5. The wounded left in the battlefield will be bandaged and cured if possible by the LA medical-men.<br>
6. The dead left in the battlefield will be given proper funeral and their graves taken care of.<br><br>
The High Command of the SVNLA<br><br>
(SECOND DOCUMENT FOLLOWS)<br><br>
                      AMERICAN SERVICEMEN<br><br>
Recently, on the night of March 31, 1968 Johnson declared that he has ordered the bombing over north Vietnam be limited and offered to go to a peace talking with the government of the Democratic republic of Vietnam for the settlement of the Vietnam problem.<br>
The reasons that caused Johnson to take this decision are quite obvious:<br>
-He has suffered heavy military setbacks in the Vietnam war, notably since Feb. 1968 when the South Vietnam people and their armed forces have launched violent attacks over all the cities of South Vietnam.<br>
-The U.S. aggressive policy in Vietnam has been steadily criticized from all sides, and the large - scale drive of the American and the world people against the U.S. aggressive war in Vietnam has made the Johnson warseeking clique more isolated than ever.<br>
By declaring a limited bombing, Johnson aims at soothing and deceiving the public opinion in the United States and in the world<br><br>
(on the other side of the leaflet it continues)<br><br>
The fact is Johnson still contemplates sending 13.500 additional troops to South Vietnam, and U.S. planes continue to raid many areas in North Vietnam.<br>
GI's You are to realize the dangerous path Johnson is leading you into.<br>
Don't indulge in the vain hope of Johnson's fake peace. Join your compatriot's in opposing this dirty war which is going against the U.S. people's interest's and aspirations.<br>
Refuse to fight.<br>
Demand the U.S. government to bring you back without any delay. At least, do keep a neutral stance as regards to the Vietnamese struggle for the overthrow of the Thieu-Ky dictatorship.<br>
Don't interfere in the Vietnamese internal affairs.<br>
Cross over to the Liberation armed forces side whenever possible. You will be treated Kindly and helped to return home or go to any other country you like.<br>
The National Front for Liberation of <br>
 Quang-nam -Da-nang<br><br>
(THIRD DOCUMENT FOLLOWS)<br><br>
                              PROCLAMATION<br><br>
                    American officers and men,<br>
                  U.S. Allied officers and men.<br><br>
For the Sake of peace and sovereignty of their country, the South Vietnam people of all strata have risen up to overthrow the present dictatorial corrupt administration, criminal of the merciless war which is heavily devastating their Fatherland.<br>
The Saigon administration is overthrown. It has now no legal nor political poWer.<br>
A new administration has been established.<br>
-Peace and neutrality for South Vietnam!<br>
-Real sovereignty for South Vietnam  !<br>
That is the sole goal of the new regime.<br>
That is the legitimate aspirations and sacred inviolable rights of the Vietnamese people; that is the South Vietnam affairs which no one has the right to interfere in.<br><br>
American Servicemen,<br>
U.S. Allied armymen,<br>
Support the struggle !<br>
Cease fire all over the South Vietnam territory !<br>
Don't do anything to carry out any order in opposition to our struggle!<br>
Respect  the South Vietnam people's internal affairs.<br>
In so doing you are in the right, moral way; It is also the <br>
uniquely proper behaviour   for the time being.<br>
The leaders of the new administration are ready to get in touch with your commanders to effectively settle the question concerning the U.S. and allied troops now present in South Vietnam.<br><br>
American and U.S. Allied armymen,<br>
The South Vietnam people wish to live and work freely and in security on the land they inherit from their ancestors, to be an<br><br>
(on the other side of the leaflet it continues)<br><br>
equal member in the large family of nations the world over, to contribute their share to the common progress of mankind.  No one has the right or is able to oppose this noble wish of peoples, should he want to.<br>
The South Vietnam people understand the history of the United States clearly and respect the freedom-loving tradition of the American people. The South Vietnam people are Willing to have friendly relations with the American people as Well as other peoples of the world.<br>
Our struggle aims at achieving the legitimate ideal of a  nation, the ideal that over a century ago Washington and Lincoln had struggled for to preserve the United States of America.<br><br>
American and U.S. allied armymen,<br>
A warless  but really sovereign South Vietnam with true neutrality is a decisive codition for you to get out of this damned war, to return home and serve your country worthily.<br>
We have Worked and are working for such a South Vietnam.<br>
Support us !<br>
Act upon the dictates of your conscience and reason !<br>
Don't interfere in the internal affairs of South Vietnam.<br><br>
(These are samples of the many different leaflets dropped along jungle trails in South Vietnam in hopes that American servicemen would find them and believe them. Neither the American fighting men or the people of South Vietnam were taken in by these leaflets. They had their greatest impact in the United States when they were embraced as truth by war protestors and seen as evidence that the North's intentions in South Vietnam was honorable. History has revealed that all this was nothing more then pure Communist Propaganda). <br><br>

